'''Plaza Miserere''' (officially ''Plaza de Miserere'') is a station on [[Line A (Buenos Aires Metro)|Line A]] of the [[Buenos Aires Metro]] <ref>[http://www.sbase.com.ar/en/index.php/the-network/line-a/85-line-a-stations/87-estaciones-lineaa-plaza-miserere Plaza Miserere Station] SubterrÃ¡neos de Buenos Aires S.E. </ref>. The station is located between [[Alberti (Buenos Aires Metro)|Alberti]] and [[Loria (Buenos Aires Metro)|Loria]] / [[Pasco (Buenos Aires Metro)|Pasco]] stations on the [[Line A (Buenos Aires)|A line]] metro. Plaza Miserere has [[Interchange station|interchange]] with [[Once (Buenos Aires Metro)|Once]] metro station of the [[Line H (Buenos Aires)|H line]] and connection to the [[Sarmiento Line (Buenos Aires)|Sarmiento line]] commuter rail service within the large station.<ref>[http://www.enelsubte.com/noticias/habilitan-el-anden-norte-plaza-miserere-718 Habilitan el andÃ©n norte de Plaza Miserere] (Spanish) Retrieved 2010-11-03</ref>
It is located at the intersection of [[Rivadavia Avenue|Rivadavia]] and [[PueyrredÃ³n Avenue|PueyrredÃ³n]] avenues, under the popular [[Plaza Miserere]], in the neighborhood of [[Balvanera]]. The station zone is a shopping precinct and in its vicinity are the French Hospital and the [[Once railway station]] of the [[Ferrocarril Domingo Faustino Sarmiento|Sarmiento Railway]]. This station belonged to the first section of Line A opened on 1 December 1913, linking this station and the [[Plaza de Mayo (Buenos Aires Metro)|Plaza de Mayo]] station.
In 1997 the station was declared a national historic monument.<ref>[http://infoleg.gov.ar/infolegInternet/anexos/40000-44999/43370/norma.htm Decreto 437/97] (Spanish) Retrieved 2010-10-29</ref>
==History== When the [[Anglo-Argentine Tramways Company]] (''CompaÃ±Ã­a de TranvÃ­as Anglo-Argentina'', in Spanish) inaugurated on 1 December 1913 its Line 1 (Today, Line A of the subway), Plaza Onceâtoday Miserereâwas the terminus, and thanks to an agreement with the company's [[Buenos Aires Western Railway]] (''Ferrocarril Oeste de Buenos Aires'', in Spanish)âSarmiento todayâit was possible the design and construction of the subway station with the possibility of being used in a synchronized manner for both modes of transport. To do this, it was built with 6 tracks (4 for the subway and 2 for the train) and 4 platforms (2 lateral and two central).
